    <p class="small">Related: <a href="/brands/traeger/">Traeger brand hub</a> · <a href="/brands/weber-grill-repair/">Weber gas grill (different architecture)</a> · <a href="/brands/wolf-outdoor-grill-repair/">Wolf outdoor grill (gas)</a> · <a href="/brands/fire-magic-grill-repair/">Fire Magic (gas)</a> · <a href="/services/bbq-grill-repair/">BBQ grill repair (service hub)</a>.</p>
  </div></section>

  <section class="section alt"><div class="wrap narrow">
    <h2>Pellet-grill architecture — why diagnostic order matters</h2>
    <p>Pellet grills like Traeger + Pit Boss + Green Mountain Grills operate on a different combustion architecture from gas grills. When a customer calls saying \"my grill won't heat up,\" the gas-grill diagnostic starting point (propane tank → burner tube → igniter → gas valve) doesn't apply. The pellet-grill sequence we run is: (1) <b>pellet moisture + hopper level</b> — wet pellets won't feed properly, empty hopper obviously won't; (2) <b>auger feed mechanism</b> — is it turning? Is it clogged? Is the shear pin intact? (3) <b>firepot condition</b> — ash buildup blocks airflow even when fan is working; cleaning service often resolves; (4) <b>hot-rod igniter</b> — resistance check; (5) <b>induction fan</b> — spin under load; (6) <b>RTD probe + PID controller</b> — feedback loop validation; (7) <b>WiFIRE firmware</b> — sequence or pairing issues. Following this protocol, ~60% of Traeger \"won't heat\" calls resolve at step 1 (moisture + hopper) or step 3 (firepot cleaning) without any parts replacement. We don't upsell when a cleaning service is the right answer.</p>
  </div></section>

